================================================================================
REVIEWED SUMMARY (reviewed — unverified items marked NOT VERIFIED)
================================================================================

C++ emRef.h: intrusive reference-counted smart pointer.

158 files outside emCore use this type — the second most pervasive
type after emString.

C++ provides:
  emRefTarget — base class that objects inherit to be ref-counted.
    Adds Alloc()/Free()/GetRefCount(). Destructor is fatal if
    refcount != 0.
  emRef<T>    — smart pointer that calls Alloc on construction/copy
    and Free on destruction/rebind.

Rust equivalent (verified):
  emRef<T>       -> Rc<T> or Rc<RefCell<T>>
    emScreen.rs:165       — Rc<RefCell<emScreen>>
    emFpPlugin.rs:445     — Rc<RefCell<Self>>
    emCoreConfig.rs:215   — Rc<RefCell<emConfigModel<Self>>>
    emContext.rs:40        — Weak<emContext> (non-owning ref)
  emRefTarget    -> no explicit base class. Rc handles refcounting
    internally.

No Rust equivalent exists for:
  emRefTarget as explicit base class — Rc<T> doesn't require T to
    inherit anything.
  emRef::Set(ptr) / Reset() — explicit rebinding. Rust uses
    variable reassignment.
  GetRefCount() — Rc::strong_count() exists but is not used in the
    Rust codebase (verified by grep: no strong_count calls found).

Open question investigated: "emRef<emVarModel<emRef<T>>> nested pattern"
  The agent's question contained an error — the actual C++ pattern is
  emRef<emVarModel<T>>, not doubly-nested. Found in:
    emBorder.h:413 — emRef<emVarModel<TkResources>>
    emVarModel.h:46 — static emRef<emVarModel<VAR>> Acquire(...)
  Rust equivalent: emVarModel is ported as WatchedVar<T>
  (emVarModel.rs:7), embedded as a struct field rather than wrapped
  in Rc<RefCell<>>. The C++ ref-counted shared model pattern is
  replaced by direct ownership.
  NOT VERIFIED: whether this ownership change affects any code path
  that shares an emVarModel across multiple consumers via emRef.
